		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Gnome Warriors (levels 1-20)</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:kukuman@darktech.org">Zaboblen</a> | 
		            2/7/2000 6:19:12 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Greetings, and well met. You are probably reading this either because you are playing a Gnome Warrior, you are bored, or you are wondering why the heck would one want to play a Gnome Warrior in the first place.<BR>
<BR>
First off, if you're bored, go play EQ, and if EQ's down, go play Unreal Tournament.<BR>
<BR>
Now, if you're wondering why you would play a Gnome Warrior, here's why.<BR>
<BR>
Gnomes aren't the best at Rogues and plain casters, and they just stink at Clerics due to their atrocious Wisdom. However, they make exceptional Warriors.<BR>
<BR>
My analysis of the stats that matter:<BR>
<BR>
Strength - 70. I personally raised it to 85. Then, I got a Spiked Collar and two Silver Amber Rings, raising my strength to 92. I am still frequently encumbered, though. Strength isn't the be all, end all stat it is in other RPGs. It determines how much you can carry and how often you hit for high damage.<BR>
<BR>
Stamina - 80. I raised it to 85. Stamina determines your hit points and how long you can fight/run/go without food and water.<BR>
<BR>
Agility - 90. I think I left this alone. Agility determines how often you Dodge and how often the enemy hits you. Gnomes are very good in this area.<BR>
<BR>
Dexterity - 85. I think I raised this to 95. This determines how often you parry, riposte, and do Critical Hits and Crippling Blows. My Gnome does WAY more critical hits than any other Warrior I have seen. I often do about two to three of them per monster, more if the monster in question has a lot of hit points.<BR>
<BR>
Intelligence - 98. You may be wondering, &quot;Why does this matter for Warriors?&quot; True, they don't cast spells, but Gnomes are the smartest light race that can be Warriors. My skills are ALWAYS maxed, except Taunt which I just learned a couple of levels ago(Stupid Me!), which is already in the mid 60s. Compare this to the Ogre and the Troll, who have 60 INT and 52 INT, respectively.<BR>
---<BR>
<BR>
Anyway, on to the level guide.<BR>
<BR>
1 and 2: Forget what people tell you about going to the Mines of Malfunction. Sure, it's in Ak'Anon so you don't have to zone, but it's infested with Necromancers and Gnome Skeletons that are invincible. When you exit Ak'Anon, continue along the path and turn on the first left. There will be a big valley, and nearby there will be a Druid circle(not ruins!) and a kobold camp. Fight large rats and kobold runts in level 1, and at level 2 fight spiderlings(CON THEM FIRST). Make sure you use Kick a lot, because it is very, very useful.<BR>
<BR>
NOTE: On some servers, some people kill Gnome guards. This is both good and bad. The good part is that these guards often carry short swords and small shields, which you can either use or sell for a total of about 3 platinum. The short swords that they drop are much better than your newbie item, and the shield is just good to have. These high level players have amassed fortunes of somewhere in the thousands of platinum, and 3 or 4 platinum is next to nothing to them. They often leave guard corpses laying on the ground. Loot them. You'll be glad you did. Just leave the cards they drop there. The bad part is, obviously, there is nobody to save you when you are in trouble. At these levels, dying is but a nuisance. Either let yourself die, or if you must live, run to the Ak'Anon zone.<BR>
<BR>
3 and 4: Steamfont stinks. Make the very short trip to Kelethin. Walk straight on the path. You will enter Lesser Faydark eventually. Now, don't follow the path here. It's long, and you will get lost or even killed. Turn right about 45 degrees and run straight. You will see the entrance to Greater Faydark. When you enter Greater Faydark, walk on the short path a ways, then turn right. Follow the path.<BR>
<BR>
Fight Wasps, Bats, and the occasional decaying skeleton and pixie trickster outside the lifts in Kelethin. SAVE THE BAT WINGS. People buy them in large quantities, as they are a quest item. People pay a lot for them, much more than you would get at the merchant. MAKE SURE YOU GET A BIND IN KELETHIN. That way, if you die, you won't have to run all the way from Ak'Anon to get your corpse. Instead, you'd be right in the place you died.<BR>
<BR>
5-7: Go to Orc Hill. This place is THE BEST. Seriously. Forget Crushbone, there are very few centurions there. You can either get a group, or you can even solo it. Look around the many camps of Orc Hill, and you will find many empty camps.<BR>
<BR>
8-11: Move to Freeport. Get a bind there. Fight in Befallen at level 8, or the orc camps in East Commons at any other level. To get to Befallen, walk along the desert wall of East Commons. You will enter West Commons. Continue to walk along the wall, keeping an eye out for the occasional griffin or hill giant, until you see an eerie blueish glow. Enter the hole that you see, and you will be there. STAY ON THE FIRST FLOOR and DO NOT GO IN THE RAT ROOM. The rats here are much more ill-tempered than the ones you encountered in Steamfont, and some even give you disease. Kill skeletons and putrid skeletons. Kill decaying skeletons. They are placeholders for the stuff you want to fight.<BR>
<BR>
Now, the orc camps. There are two orc camps in East Commons, one is referred to as the &quot;large&quot; and one the &quot;small&quot;. They are both on the green wall opposite of the desert wall. The large one is the first one you encounter coming from Freeport. The small is the last one. These are excellent exp and loot in a group. When you get to loot, if you get Deathfist Belts, don't sell them! Turn them in to Captain Hezlan in the Freeport Militia House. You will get better faction with the Freeport Militia, and their merchant allies. You will get lower faction with the Paladins of North Freeport, but the change is so slight you will not notice much.<BR>
<BR>
12-14: These levels are a bit different than most.<BR>
<BR>
Get LOADS of food and water. If you can, get 20 of each. You will need them. Get on the boat to Butcherblock. You will see two VERY big rocks. Jump off at this. Trust me on this. Go to the rock on the left, and unless you are ready for a fight, watch out for the goblins. Fight the alluring siren on this rock. They are EXCELLENT exp and OK loot. When you get level 13, wait near the strait where the boat passes through. When you see the boat, position yourself directly in it's way. You will get picked up by the boat. Wait, and when you get back to Freeport, go to the trainer and dump all of your points into DUAL WIELD! My suggestion is that you get two Langseaxes. They are DMG 6, Delay 23(!!). I often hit for 12, sometimes the max of 13. They are relatively cheap(I picked both up for 70pp total, but you could probably get a better deal) and are also pretty common as it is a simple quest that involves killing a simple level 20 or so mob. Resupply, and continue. When you get level 14, go back, resupply, and come back.<BR>
<BR>
15: When you get 15, instead of going back to Freeport, get off at Butcherblock. Go into Kaladim, dump all of your points into DOUBLE ATTACK(Dual Wield with one weapon!), and continue on. Get a bind in Kelethin. Get a group to fight Legionnaires, Emissaries, Oracles, and Lord Darish in the Throne Room of the castle in Crushbone. If you get Crushbone Belts and/or Legionnaire Shoulderpads, don't sell them(sell Legionnaire Bracers unless you have another use for them)! They are quest items in Kaladim. Turn each CB Belt into Canloe Nusback in the Warrior Guild in Kaladim. Turn two or multiples of two Legionnaire Shoulderpads in to the same person. They give even better exp and items/coins than the Deathfist Belt quest in Freeport. If you want, you can even camp the orc trainer on Trainer Hill(off-peak hours only) to get a Shiny Brass Shield, which sell for a decent amount.<BR>
<BR>
16-20: Go back to Freeport. Get a bind. Go to Oasis of Marr. Run along the water in North Ro. Solo caimans(until 18), crocodiles, Deepwater Caimans(not at 16), and Deepwater Crocodiles(not until 18 or 19, if even then). Forget orc highway. That place gives crap exp, not great loot(occasional raw-hide items), and is tough without a group. Watch out for Sand Giants. Sometimes idiots train spectres to the docks. Spectres look like floating Grim Reapers with tails. If you see one, RUN.<BR>
<BR>
There is a trick to finding things to fight here! These reptiles often spawn in the ocean. Get yourself a decent bow and a lot of arrows. If you are partially under water and partially above, you can see the entire ocean as far as your clipping plane allows it, so you can spot reptiles MUCH easier. Caimans are the most frequently spotted down here, with the occasional crocodile and the very rare deepwater.<BR>
<BR>
At level 18 you have a choice. You can either stay in Oasis, or if you are growing tired of not finding things to fight, you can go to Lake Rathe, South Karana, or Highpass Hold for Orcs. If you choose Lake Rathe or South Karana, get a bind in the Arena. If you choose Highpass, get a bind in Highpass. IF YOU CHOOSE HIGHPASS: don't hang out near the entrance! I have been killed MANY times by orcs wandering around the entrance. The guards here are not very strong and will not always do the job quickly enough.<BR>
<BR>
That's it for now! Hope you have fun with your Gnome Warrior!<BR>
<BR>
Zaboblen &lt;Ronin&gt;<BR>
Pending Last Names: &quot;Impayrd'Lompa&quot; or &quot;Uumpa'Luumpa&quot;<BR>
17th Level - Tunare Server<BR>

